<Layout title="Shannon 5 — KL Divergence" favicon="📡">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/information-theory/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to information theory</a>

    <h1>KL Divergence</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Shannon 1948 (public domain) &middot; Wikipedia (CC BY-SA 4.0)</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kullback%E2%80%93Leibler_divergence"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>KL divergence</a> measures the <strong>extra surprise</strong> you get when you use distribution Q to code data that actually comes from P. It is not a distance: D(P||Q) &ne; D(Q||P). It is always &ge; 0, and zero only when P = Q.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- 1. Definition -->
    <h3>The formula</h3>
    <p>D<sub>KL</sub>(P || Q) = &sum; P(x) log(P(x) / Q(x)). Each term weights the log-ratio by how likely x actually is under P. When Q assigns low probability to something P considers likely, that term blows up. When Q matches P perfectly, every ratio is 1 and every log is 0.</p>

    <!-- SVG: Two distributions P and Q overlaid -->
    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 400 200" class="w-full max-w-md" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <!-- Axes -->
        <line x1="50" y1="170" x2="370" y2="170" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.3"/>
        <line x1="50" y1="170" x2="50" y2="20" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1" stroke-opacity="0.3"/>
        <!-- P bars (blue, left-shifted) -->
        <rect x="75" y="50" width="25" height="120" rx="2" fill="#3b82f6" fill-opacity="0.35" stroke="#3b82f6" stroke-width="1"/>
        <rect x="135" y="80" width="25" height="90" rx="2" fill="#3b82f6" fill-opacity="0.35" stroke="#3b82f6" stroke-width="1"/>
        <rect x="195" y="120" width="25" height="50" rx="2" fill="#3b82f6" fill-opacity="0.35" stroke="#3b82f6" stroke-width="1"/>
        <rect x="255" y="145" width="25" height="25" rx="2" fill="#3b82f6" fill-opacity="0.35" stroke="#3b82f6" stroke-width="1"/>
        <rect x="315" y="160" width="25" height="10" rx="2" fill="#3b82f6" fill-opacity="0.35" stroke="#3b82f6" stroke-width="1"/>
        <!-- Q bars (red, right-shifted) -->
        <rect x="100" y="130" width="25" height="40" rx="2" fill="#ef4444" fill-opacity="0.35" stroke="#ef4444" stroke-width="1"/>
        <rect x="160" y="90" width="25" height="80" rx="2" fill="#ef4444" fill-opacity="0.35" stroke="#ef4444" stroke-width="1"/>
        <rect x="220" y="60" width="25" height="110" rx="2" fill="#ef4444" fill-opacity="0.35" stroke="#ef4444" stroke-width="1"/>
        <rect x="280" y="90" width="25" height="80" rx="2" fill="#ef4444" fill-opacity="0.35" stroke="#ef4444" stroke-width="1"/>
        <rect x="340" y="130" width="25" height="40" rx="2" fill="#ef4444" fill-opacity="0.35" stroke="#ef4444" stroke-width="1"/>
        <!-- Divergence shading between bars where P > Q -->
        <rect x="75" y="50" width="50" height="80" rx="0" fill="#fbbf24" fill-opacity="0.12"/>
        <!-- Labels -->
        <text x="88" y="42" text-anchor="middle" fill="#60a5fa" font-size="11">P</text>
        <text x="113" y="125" text-anchor="middle" fill="#ef4444" font-size="11">Q</text>
        <!-- Legend -->
        <rect x="60" y="8" width="10" height="10" fill="#3b82f6" fill-opacity="0.5"/>
        <text x="75" y="17" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.6">P (truth)</text>
        <rect x="150" y="8" width="10" height="10" fill="#ef4444" fill-opacity="0.5"/>
        <text x="165" y="17" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.6">Q (model)</text>
        <rect x="240" y="8" width="10" height="10" fill="#fbbf24" fill-opacity="0.3"/>
        <text x="255" y="17" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.6">divergence</text>
        <!-- x labels -->
        <text x="90" y="186" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">a</text>
        <text x="150" y="186" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">b</text>
        <text x="210" y="186" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">c</text>
        <text x="270" y="186" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">d</text>
        <text x="330" y="186" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.4">e</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; KL divergence: D(P||Q) = sum P(x) * log2(P(x)/Q(x))
(define (log2 x) (/ (log x) (log 2)))

(define (kl-divergence p q)
  (apply + (map (lambda (pi qi)
    (if (> pi 0) (* pi (log2 (/ pi qi))) 0))
  p q)))

; P = truth, Q = model
(define P '(0.4 0.3 0.15 0.1 0.05))
(define Q '(0.1 0.2 0.3 0.25 0.15))

(display "D(P||Q) = ") (display (kl-divergence P Q)) (newline)
(display "D(Q||P) = ") (display (kl-divergence Q P)) (newline)
; Not equal — KL divergence is asymmetric.

; D(P||P) should be 0
(display "D(P||P) = ") (display (kl-divergence P P)) (newline)
; Zero: no extra surprise when the model matches the truth.
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`import math

def kl_divergence(p, q):
    return sum(pi * math.log2(pi / qi) for pi, qi in zip(p, q) if pi > 0)

P = [0.4, 0.3, 0.15, 0.1, 0.05]
Q = [0.1, 0.2, 0.3, 0.25, 0.15]

print(f"D(P||Q) = {kl_divergence(P, Q):.4f}")
print(f"D(Q||P) = {kl_divergence(Q, P):.4f}")
print(f"D(P||P) = {kl_divergence(P, P):.4f}")
print("Asymmetric: D(P||Q) != D(Q||P). Not a distance.")
`} />
    </div>

    <!-- 2. Gibbs' inequality -->
    <h3>Gibbs' inequality: always non-negative</h3>
    <p>KL divergence is always &ge; 0. This is <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gibbs%27_inequality"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Gibbs' inequality</a>. The proof uses <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jensen%27s_inequality"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Jensen's inequality</a> on the concavity of log. Intuitively: you can never do <em>better</em> than the truth. Any mismatch between model and reality costs you bits.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Gibbs' inequality: D(P||Q) >= 0 always
(define (log2 x) (/ (log x) (log 2)))

(define (kl-divergence p q)
  (apply + (map (lambda (pi qi)
    (if (> pi 0) (* pi (log2 (/ pi qi))) 0))
  p q)))

; Try many random-ish distributions — all non-negative
(define (check p q label)
  (let ((d (kl-divergence p q)))
    (display label) (display ": D = ")
    (display d) (display (if (>= d 0) "  ok" "  FAIL"))
    (newline)))

(check '(0.5 0.5)     '(0.5 0.5)     "uniform vs uniform")
(check '(0.9 0.1)     '(0.5 0.5)     "biased vs uniform ")
(check '(0.5 0.5)     '(0.9 0.1)     "uniform vs biased ")
(check '(0.7 0.2 0.1) '(0.1 0.2 0.7) "flipped           ")
; All >= 0. Gibbs' inequality holds.
`} />

    <!-- 3. Asymmetry -->
    <h3>Not a distance</h3>
    <p>A true distance satisfies d(x,y) = d(y,x). KL divergence does not. D(P||Q) asks "how surprised am I using Q when P is true?" while D(Q||P) asks the reverse. These are different questions with different answers. Using a bad model for rare events is worse than using one for common events.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Asymmetry: D(P||Q) != D(Q||P) in general
(define (log2 x) (/ (log x) (log 2)))

(define (kl-divergence p q)
  (apply + (map (lambda (pi qi)
    (if (> pi 0) (* pi (log2 (/ pi qi))) 0))
  p q)))

; P concentrates on outcome 1. Q spreads evenly.
(define P '(0.9 0.05 0.05))
(define Q '(0.33 0.34 0.33))

(display "D(P||Q) = ") (display (kl-divergence P Q)) (newline)
(display "D(Q||P) = ") (display (kl-divergence Q P)) (newline)
(display "ratio   = ") (display (/ (kl-divergence P Q) (kl-divergence Q P)))
; Very different. Direction matters.
`} />

